problem:
Regarding rare earth elements, which of the following statements is correct?
(A) The entire d-subshell is filled with electrons
(B) Because their valence electrons are filled in the 4f subshell, they are difficult to identify using chemical methods;
(C) They all belong to Group II elements;
(D) They are semiconductors.

solution:
According to the problem, the ground state hydrogen atom is excited to the \( n=5 \) state.

$$
\begin{aligned}
h \nu & = R_{\mathrm{H}} h c \left( \frac{1}{1^2} - \frac{1}{5^2} \right) \\
& = 13.6 \times \left( \frac{1}{1} - \frac{1}{25} \right) = 13.06 \ \mathrm{eV}
\end{aligned}
$$

The spectral terms for the lithium atom are

$$
T_{3 \mathrm{s}}=\frac{R}{\left(3-\Delta_{\mathrm{s}}\right)^{2}}, \quad T_{2 \mathrm{p}}=\frac{R}{\left(2-\Delta_{\mathrm{p}}\right)^{2}}
$$

The wavenumber of the spectral line for the transition from the 3s state to the 2p state is

$$
\begin{aligned}
\tilde{\nu}_{3 \mathrm{s} \rightarrow 2 \mathrm{p}} & = T_{2 \mathrm{p}} - T_{3 \mathrm{s}} = \frac{R}{\left(2-\Delta_{\mathrm{p}}\right)^{2}} - \frac{R}{\left(3-\Delta_{\mathrm{s}}\right)^{2}} \\
& = \frac{13.6 \times 10^{10}}{12400 \times (2-0.05)^{2}} - \frac{13.6 \times 10^{10}}{12400 \times (3-0.40)^{2}} \\
& = 1.26 \times 10^{6} \, \mathrm{m}^{-1}
\end{aligned}
$$

The formula for the energy levels of a hydrogen atom is  

\[
\begin{gathered}
E_{n}=-\frac{1}{2} \alpha^{2} m_{\mathrm{e}} c^{2} \frac{Z^{2}}{n^{2}}=-\frac{A}{n^{2}} \\
A=\frac{1}{2} m_{\mathrm{e}} c^{2} \alpha^{2} Z^{2}
\end{gathered}
\]

The answer is (D).

The change in wavelength due to Compton scattering is independent of the wavelength of the incident light. The change in wavelength is maximum when the scattering angle $\theta=180^{\circ}$.

$$
\begin{aligned}
\Delta \lambda_{\mathrm{m}} & =\frac{h}{m_{\mathrm{e}} c}\left(1-\cos 180^{\circ}\right)=\frac{2 h}{m_{\mathrm{e}} c} \\
& =\frac{2 \times 1.24 \, \text{keV} \cdot \text{nm}}{0.511 \, \text{MeV}}=0.00485 \, \text{nm}
\end{aligned}
$$

The energy difference between the incident photon and the scattered photon, which is the maximum energy of the recoiling electron, is

$$
E_{\mathrm{k}}=\Delta E_{\nu}=\frac{h c}{\lambda}-\frac{h c}{\lambda^{\prime}}=\frac{h c}{\lambda} \cdot \frac{\Delta \lambda}{(\lambda+\Delta \lambda)}
$$

For the X-ray with $\lambda_{1}=0.050 \, \text{nm}$,

$$
E_{\mathrm{k}_{1}}=\frac{h c}{\lambda_{1}} \cdot \frac{\Delta \lambda}{\left(\lambda_{1}+\Delta \lambda\right)}=\frac{1.24 \, \text{keV} \cdot \text{nm}}{0.050 \, \text{nm}} \cdot \frac{0.00485 \, \text{nm}}{(0.050 + 0.00485) \, \text{nm}}=2.2 \, \text{keV}
$$

Let \(\nu = 1058 \times 10^{6} \, \text{Hz}\), the Lamb shift is the energy level difference between \( ^{2}S_{1/2} \) and \( ^{2}P_{1/2} \), given by \(\Delta E_{1} = h \nu\). The energy level difference between \( ^{2}P_{3/2} \) and \( ^{2}P_{1/2} \) is

\[
\begin{aligned}
\Delta E_{2} & = \frac{\Delta E_{1}}{0.10} = \frac{h \nu}{0.10} \\
& = \frac{6.626 \times 10^{-34} \times 1058 \times 10^{6}}{0.10 \times 1.602 \times 10^{-19}} \\
& \approx 4.4 \times 10^{-5} \, \text{eV}
\end{aligned}
\]

The spectral terms for the lithium atom are given by

$$
T_{2 \mathrm{s}}=\frac{R}{\left(2-\Delta_{\mathrm{s}}\right)^{2}}, \quad T_{2 \mathrm{p}}=\frac{R}{\left(2-\Delta_{\mathrm{p}}\right)^{2}}
$$

The wavenumber of the transition from the 2p state to the 2s state is

$$
\begin{aligned}
\tilde{\nu}_{2 \mathrm{p} \rightarrow 2 \mathrm{s}} & = T_{2 \mathrm{s}} - T_{2 \mathrm{p}} = \frac{R}{\left(2-\Delta_{\mathrm{s}}\right)^{2}} - \frac{R}{\left(2-\Delta_{\mathrm{p}}\right)^{2}} \\
& = \frac{13.6 \times 10^{10}}{12400 \times (2-0.40)^{2}} - \frac{13.6 \times 10^{10}}{12400 \times (2-0.05)^{2}} \\
& = 1.40 \times 10^{6} \, \mathrm{m}^{-1}
\end{aligned}
$$

At $T = 300 \mathrm{~K}$, the average kinetic energy of the proton is

$$
\begin{aligned}
E_{\mathrm{k}} &= \frac{3}{2} k T = 1.38 \times 10^{-23} \times 300 = 6.21 \times 10^{-21}\, \mathrm{J} \\
\lambda_{\mathrm{p}} &= \frac{h}{p} = \frac{h}{\sqrt{2 m E_{\mathrm{k}}}} = \frac{6.63 \times 10^{-34}}{\sqrt{2 \times 1.67 \times 10^{-27} \times 6.21 \times 10^{-21}}} \, \mathrm{m} = 0.105\, \mathrm{nm}
\end{aligned}
$$

or

$$
\begin{aligned}
E_{\mathrm{k}} &= \frac{3}{2} k T = \frac{3}{2} \times 8.6 \times 10^{-5} \times 300 = 3.87 \times 10^{-2}\, \mathrm{eV} \\
\lambda_{\mathrm{p}} &= \frac{h}{p} = \frac{h c}{\sqrt{2 m c^{2} E_{\mathrm{k}}}} = \frac{1.24 \times 10^{3}}{\sqrt{2 \times 938 \times 10^{6} \times 3.87 \times 10^{-2}}} \, \mathrm{nm} = 0.105\, \mathrm{nm}
\end{aligned}
$$

The formula for Compton scattering is

$$
\Delta \lambda = \lambda - \lambda_0 = \frac{h}{m_e c}(1 - \cos \theta)
$$

where the Compton wavelength is

$$
\lambda_{\mathrm{C}} = \frac{h}{m_{\mathrm{e}} c} = 2.4263 \times 10^{-12} \, \mathrm{m}
$$

From this, the wavelength $\lambda_{\pi/2}$ of the X-ray scattered in the $\theta = \pi/2$ direction and the energy gained by the recoil electron $\Delta E_{\pi/2}$ are given by:

$$
\begin{aligned}
\lambda_{\pi/2} &= \lambda_0 + \lambda_{\mathrm{C}}(1 - \cos(\pi/2)) = \lambda_0 + \lambda_{\mathrm{C}} = 0.0732 \, \mathrm{nm} \\
\end{aligned}
$$

The energy gained by the recoil electron is:

$$
\begin{aligned}
\Delta E_{\pi/2} &= h \nu_0 - h \nu = \frac{hc}{\lambda_0} - \frac{hc}{\lambda_{\pi/2}} = 1240 \left( \frac{1}{0.0708} - \frac{1}{0.0732} \right) = 574.2 \, \mathrm{eV}
\end{aligned}
$$

$$
\begin{aligned}
\Delta E &= \frac{4}{5} \times 82^{2} \times 13.6 \mathrm{~eV} \times \left(\frac{1.2 \times 10^{-15} \times 208^{1/3}}{0.529 \times 10^{-10}}\right)^{2} \\
&= 8.89 \mathrm{eV} \\
\Delta \tilde{\nu} &= \frac{\Delta E}{hc} \approx 7.2 \times 10^{4} \mathrm{~cm}^{-1}
\end{aligned}
$$

Given $s_{1}=s_{2}=s_{3}=\frac{1}{2}, l_{1}=l_{2}=l_{3}=1$, each electron can have six possible states:

$$
\begin{aligned}
& m_{l}=1, \quad m_{l}=0, \quad m_{l}=-1 \\
& m_{s}= \pm \frac{1}{2}, \quad m_{s}= \pm \frac{1}{2}, \quad m_{s}= \pm \frac{1}{2}
\end{aligned}
$$

According to the Pauli exclusion principle, the three electrons can only be in three different states out of these six possible states. The total orbital magnetic quantum number and the total spin magnetic quantum number from these combinations are given by

$$
M_{L}=\sum_{i=1}^{3} m_{l i}, \quad M_{S}=\sum_{i=1}^{3} m_{s i}
$$

Since repeating combinations of $M_{L}$ and $M_{S}$ do not generate new quantum states, they can be omitted. The corresponding values of $M_{L}$ and $M_{S}$ obtained are:

$$
\begin{aligned}
& M_{L}=2, \quad 1, \quad 0 \\
& M_{S}=\frac{1}{2}, \frac{3}{2}
\end{aligned}
$$

The difference in the reduced mass of ${ }^{1} \mathrm{H}$ and ${ }^{2} \mathrm{H}$ is

$$
\begin{gathered}
\Delta \mu=\frac{M_{\mathrm{D}} m_{\mathrm{e}}}{M_{\mathrm{D}}+m_{\mathrm{e}}}-\frac{M_{\mathrm{p}} m_{\mathrm{e}}}{M_{\mathrm{p}}+m_{\mathrm{e}}} \cong \frac{m_{\mathrm{e}}^{2}}{2 M_{\mathrm{p}}}, \\
\Delta \lambda=\lambda \frac{\Delta \mu}{\mu} \cong 6.6 \times 10^{2} \times \frac{1}{2 \times 1836}=0.18 \, \mathrm{nm}
\end{gathered}
$$

The $\mathrm{H}_{\alpha}$ line and the series limit correspond to transitions from energy levels $n = 3$ and $n = \infty$, respectively, to the energy level $n = 2$. Therefore,

$$
\begin{gathered}
\frac{\lambda_{\infty}}{\lambda_{\alpha}}=\frac{1/2^{2}-1/3^{2}}{1/2^{2}}=\frac{5}{9} \\
\lambda_{\infty}=\frac{5}{9} \lambda_{\alpha}=\frac{5}{9} \times 656.0 = 364.6 \, \text{nm}
\end{gathered}
$$

The answer is (C).

problem:
Assume the values of the lowest spectral terms of a sodium atom are (expressed in $\mathrm{cm}^{-1}$) as follows:  
3s: ${ }^{2} \mathrm{S}_{1/2} \quad 41448$; 3p: ${ }^{2} \mathrm{P}_{1/2, 3/2} \quad 24484$;  
3d: ${ }^{2} \mathrm{D}_{3/2, 5/2} \quad 12274$;  
4s: ${ }^{2} \mathrm{S}_{1/2} \quad 15705$; 4p: ${ }^{2} \mathrm{P}_{1/2, 3/2} \quad 11180$;  
4d: ${ }^{2} \mathrm{D}_{3/2, 5/2} \quad 6897$;  
4f: ${ }^{2} \mathrm{F}_{5/2, 7/2} \quad 6858$;  
5s: ${ }^{2} \mathrm{S}_{1/2} \quad 8246$; 5p: ${ }^{2} \mathrm{P}_{1/2, 3/2} \quad 6407$.

If a sodium atom is in the 3s state, can it undergo a transition when bombarded with a 3.3 eV electron?

solution:
$$
\begin{gathered}
t = \left(\frac{1}{\lambda}\right) \ln \left(\frac{N_0}{N}\right) = \left(\frac{1}{\lambda}\right) \ln (1.25) = 1 \\
\lambda = \ln (1.25) = 0.223 \\
T_{1/2} = \frac{0.693}{0.223} = 3.1 \text{ (minutes) }
\end{gathered}
$$

The answer is (B).

The Compton scattering formula is

$$
\Delta \lambda = \lambda - \lambda_0 = \frac{h}{m_e c}(1 - \cos \theta)
$$

where the Compton wavelength is

$$
\lambda_{\mathrm{C}} = \frac{h}{m_{\mathrm{e}} c} = 2.4263 \times 10^{-12} \, \mathrm{m}
$$

This gives the wavelength $\lambda_{\pi}$ of the X-rays scattered in the direction $\theta = \pi$ and the energy $\Delta E_{\pi}$ acquired by the recoil electron as follows:

$$
\begin{aligned}
\lambda_{\pi} &= \lambda_0 + \lambda_{\mathrm{C}}(1 - \cos(\pi)) = \lambda_0 + 2\lambda_{\mathrm{C}} = 0.0756 \, \mathrm{nm} 
\end{aligned}
$$

The energy acquired by the recoil electron:

$$
\begin{aligned}
\Delta E_{\pi} &= \frac{hc}{\lambda_0} - \frac{hc}{\lambda_{\pi}} = 1240 \left( \frac{1}{0.0708} - \frac{1}{0.0756} \right) = 1.112 \times 10^3 \, \mathrm{eV}
\end{aligned}
$$

problem:
Assume the lowest spectral terms of a sodium atom in terms of their values (expressed in $\mathrm{cm}^{-1}$):
3s: ${ }^{2} \mathrm{S}_{1/2} \quad 41448$; 3p: ${ }^{2} \mathrm{P}_{1/2, 3/2} \quad 24484$;
3d: ${ }^{2} \mathrm{D}_{3/2, 5/2} \quad 12274$;
4s: ${ }^{2} \mathrm{S}_{1/2} \quad 15705$; 4p: ${ }^{2} \mathrm{P}_{1/2, 3/2} \quad 11180$;
4d: ${ }^{2} \mathrm{D}_{3/2, 5/2} \quad 6897$; 
4f: ${ }^{2} \mathrm{F}_{5/2, 7/2} \quad 6858$;
5s: ${ }^{2} \mathrm{S}_{1/2} \quad 8246$; 5p: ${ }^{2} \mathrm{P}_{1/2, 3/2} \quad 6407$.

Can a transition occur when irradiated with light of 412.3 nm?

solution:
For the hydrogen atom in the 2p state, \(n=2, \, l=1, \, s=\frac{1}{2}\), giving \(j_1=\frac{3}{2}, \, j_2=\frac{1}{2}\). The energy level splitting due to spin-orbit coupling is

\[
\begin{aligned}
\Delta E_{ls} &= \frac{h c R \alpha^{2}}{n^{3} l\left(l+\frac{1}{2}\right)(l+1)}\left(\frac{j_{1}\left(j_{1}+1\right)-j_{2}\left(j_{2}+1\right)}{2}\right) \\
&= \frac{13.6 \times 5.3 \times 10^{-5}}{8 \times \frac{3}{2} \times 2} \times \frac{\frac{15}{4}-\frac{3}{4}}{2} = 4.5 \times 10^{-5} \, \mathrm{eV} \\
&\approx 10^{-4} \, \mathrm{eV}
\end{aligned}
\]

where \(R\) is the Rydberg constant, \(hcR = 13.6 \, \mathrm{eV}\) is the ionization potential of hydrogen, and \(\alpha = \frac{1}{137}\) is the fine structure constant. Therefore, the answer is \(10^{-4} \, \mathrm{eV}\).

The answer is (B).

The wavelength for the series limit ($n \rightarrow \infty$) is given by
$$
\begin{gathered}
\frac{1}{\lambda_{\infty}}=4 R_{\mathrm{He}} \cdot \frac{1}{16} \\
\lambda_{\infty}=\frac{4 h c}{R_{\mathrm{He}} h c}=\frac{4 \times 1240}{13.6}=364.7 \, \mathrm{nm}
\end{gathered}
$$

The recoil of the nucleus upon emitting a $\gamma$ photon can be treated using non-relativistic physics:

$$
\begin{gathered}
p_{\gamma}=\frac{E_{\gamma}}{c}=p_{\mathrm{N}}=\sqrt{2 M E_{\gamma \mathrm{R}}} \\
E_{\gamma \mathrm{R}}=\frac{E_{\gamma}^{2}}{2 M c^{2}}=1.48 \, \text{(eV)}
\end{gathered}
$$

Let \(E_{3}, E_{2}, E_{1}\) represent the energies of the states \(2 \mathrm{P}_{3 / 2}, 2 \mathrm{P}_{1 / 2}\), and \(1 \mathrm{S}_{1 / 2}\), respectively. We have \(h \nu_{1} = E_{2} - E_{1}\) and \(h \nu_{2} = E_{3} - E_{1}\). Therefore, the frequency difference between the two spectral lines is

\[
\nu_{2} - \nu_{1} = \frac{E_{3} - E_{2}}{h} = \frac{(E_{3} - E_{2}) c}{h c} = \frac{4.5 \times 10^{-5} \times 3 \times 10^{8} \times 10^{9}}{1240} = 1.1 \times 10^{10}~\text{Hz}
\]

The wavelength difference is

\[
\lambda_{1} - \lambda_{2} = c \left(\frac{1}{\nu_{1}} - \frac{1}{\nu_{2}}\right) \approx \frac{c(\nu_{2} - \nu_{1})}{\nu_{1}^{2}} = \frac{(E_{3} - E_{2}) c}{h \nu_{1}^{2}}
\]

Where

\[
\begin{aligned}
\nu_{1} &= \frac{E_{2} - E_{1}}{h} = \frac{E_{1} / 4 - E_{1}}{h} = -\frac{3}{4} \cdot \frac{E_{1}}{h}, \quad E_{1} = -13.6 \, \text{eV} \\
\lambda_{1} - \lambda_{2} &= \frac{(E_{3} - E_{2}) c}{h} \cdot \frac{4^{2} h^{2}}{3^{2} E_{1}^{2}} = \frac{4.5 \times 10^{-5} \times 1240 \times 4^{2}}{3^{2} \times 13.6^{2}} = 5.4 \, \text{pm}
\end{aligned}
\]

According to the Geiger-Nuttall law, the relation between the energy $E_{\alpha}$ of the $\alpha$ particle and the decay constant $\lambda$ for estimating the lifetime of ${}^{197} \mathrm{Au}$ is given by

$$
\log_{10} \lambda = C - D E_{\alpha}^{-1/2}
$$

where $E_{\alpha}$ is in MeV, and $C$ and $D$ are constants related to $Z$. For a rough estimation, the constants $C$ and $D$ can be approximately substituted using the constants for Pb, with $C \sim 52$ and $D \sim 140$:

$$
\begin{gathered}
\lambda \approx 10^{\left[52 - 140 E_{\alpha}^{-1/2}\right]} \approx 10^{-25}\,(\mathrm{s}^{-1}) \\
T_{1/2} \approx \frac{\ln 2}{\lambda} \approx 6.9 \times 10^{24} \approx 2.2 \times 10^{17} \text{ years}
\end{gathered}
$$

The thermonuclear reactions inside the Sun primarily involve the proton-proton chain reaction, which can be represented as follows:

$$
\begin{gathered}
\mathrm{p}+\mathrm{p} \rightarrow \mathrm{D}+\mathrm{e}^{+}+\nu_{\mathrm{e}} \\
\mathrm{D}+\mathrm{p} \rightarrow {}^{3} \mathrm{He}+\gamma \\
{}^{3} \mathrm{He}+{}^{3} \mathrm{He} \rightarrow {}^{4} \mathrm{He}+2 \mathrm{p}
\end{gathered}
$$

The overall reaction is

$$
4 \mathrm{p} \rightarrow {}^{4} \mathrm{He}+2 \mathrm{e}^{+}+2 \nu_{\mathrm{e}}
$$

The energy released from this reaction is approximately

$$
Q=\left[4 M({}^{1} \mathrm{H})-M({}^{4} \mathrm{He})\right] c^{2} \approx 26.7\,\text{MeV}
$$

problem:
According to the nuclear shell model, predict the spin and parity of ${ }_{7}^{15} \mathrm{N}$. The nuclear shell model describes the movement under the influence of a common exponential potential, including the coupling of spin and orbital angular momentum interaction $-2aSL$. For the low-energy excited state of the exponential potential, it can be approximated by the three-dimensional harmonic oscillator energy level $E=\hbar \omega\left(m_{1}+m_{2}+m_{3}+\frac{3}{2}\right)$. The ground state is spherically symmetric with $L=0$; the first excited state is a triply degenerate state with $L=1$. After considering spin and orbital coupling, Table 2.9 provides the properties of the lowest energy levels, noting that $\mathrm{P}_{3/2}$ has a lower energy level than $\mathrm{P}_{1/2}$. Neutrons and protons are filled into the respective energy levels independently.

Table 2.9  

\begin{center}  
\begin{tabular}{c|c|c}  
\hline  
Energy Level & Degeneracy & Parity \\  
\hline  
$\mathrm{P}_{1/2}$ & 2 & -1 \\  
$\mathrm{P}_{3/2}$ & 4 & -1 \\  
$\mathrm{S}_{1/2}$ & 2 & 1 \\  
\hline  
\end{tabular}  
\end{center}

solution:
Particles are classified by the interaction they participate in and their spin:  
Leptons do not participate in the strong interaction;  
Mesons and baryons participate in all interactions, and hadrons with integer spin are called mesons, while hadrons with half-integer spin are called baryons;  
Particles with mass have gravitational interaction;  
Charged particles have electromagnetic interaction.  
The answer is (C).

For 100 keV neutrons, only S-wave scattering is relevant. From experimental data, the scattering cross-section can be determined using the attenuation formula:

$$
\begin{gathered}
I = I_{0} \mathrm{e}^{-N t \sigma} \\
\sigma = \frac{1}{N t} \ln \frac{I_{0}}{I} = \frac{\ln 2}{N t}
\end{gathered}
$$

Substituting $N t = 6.023 \times 10^{23} \times \frac{10}{12} = 5.02 \times 10^{23}$, we find $\sigma = 1.4 \times 10^{-24} \, \text{cm}^{2}$.

The number of nuclei in $1 \, \mu \mathrm{g}$ of ${}^{224} \mathrm{Ra}$ is

$$
N=\frac{10^{-6}}{224} \times 6.023 \times 10^{23}=2.69 \times 10^{15}
$$

The fraction $\eta$ of decay over a period $t$ and the number of decayed nuclei $N^{\prime}$ are expressed as

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \eta=\left(1-\mathrm{e}^{-\lambda t}\right) \times 100\% = \left(1-\mathrm{e}^{-0.693 t / T}\right) \times 100\% \\
& N^{\prime}=N-N \mathrm{e}^{-\lambda t}=N\left(1-\mathrm{e}^{-0.693 t / T}\right)
\end{aligned}
$$

Over the entire eleven days

$$
\begin{gathered}
\eta_{2}=\left(1-\mathrm{e}^{-0.693 \times 11 / 3.66}\right) \times 100\% = 87.5\% \\
N_{2}^{\prime}=N\left(1-\mathrm{e}^{-0.693 \times 11 / 3.66}\right)=2.35 \times 10^{15}
\end{gathered}
$$

The change in wavelength due to Compton scattering is independent of the wavelength of the incident light. When the scattering angle $\theta=180^{\circ}$, the change in wavelength is at its maximum:

$$
\begin{aligned}
\Delta \lambda_{\mathrm{m}} & =\frac{h}{m_{\mathrm{e}} c}\left(1-\cos 180^{\circ}\right)=\frac{2 h}{m_{\mathrm{e}} c} \\
& =\frac{2 \times 1.24 \, \text{keV} \cdot \text{nm}}{0.511 \, \text{MeV}}=0.00485 \, \text{nm}
\end{aligned}
$$

The difference in energy between the incident photon and the scattered photon, which is the maximum energy of the recoil electron, is given by:

$$
E_{\mathrm{k}}=\Delta E_{\nu}=\frac{h c}{\lambda}-\frac{h c}{\lambda^{\prime}}=\frac{h c}{\lambda} \cdot \frac{\Delta \lambda}{(\lambda+\Delta \lambda)}
$$

For visible light with $\lambda_{2}=500 \, \text{nm}$

$$
E_{\mathrm{k}_{2}}=\frac{h c}{\lambda_{2}} \cdot \frac{\Delta \lambda}{\left(\lambda_{2}+\Delta \lambda\right)} \approx \frac{1.24 \, \text{keV} \cdot \text{nm}}{500 \, \text{nm}} \cdot \frac{0.00485 \, \text{nm}}{500 \, \text{nm}}=2.4 \times 10^{-5} \, \text{eV}
$$

The calculation shows that the energy transferred to electrons by photons in the visible light range is very small and can be neglected. Therefore, for visible light, it is generally unnecessary to study their Compton scattering effects. The Compton scattering at the long-wavelength limit becomes Thomson scattering. Furthermore, at this moment, the photon's energy is so low that the bound electrons in the atom cannot be treated as stationary free electrons.

The decay of the excited nucleus is a two-body decay. By the conservation of energy and momentum, when the nucleus emits the $\gamma$ ray, the nucleus also gains a recoil momentum equal in magnitude to that of the $\gamma$ ray. Therefore, during the de-excitation process, the nucleus retains a portion of the excitation energy, which is why the $\gamma$ ray energy $E_{\gamma}$ is slightly less than the excitation energy $\Delta E$.

Let the recoil momentum of the nucleus be $p$, and the total energy of the nucleus be $E$. From the conservation of energy and momentum, we have

$$
\begin{aligned}
& p = p_{\gamma} = \frac{E_{\gamma}}{c} \\
& h \nu = E_{\gamma} = c p_{\gamma}
\end{aligned}
$$

$$
\begin{aligned}
& E = \sqrt{p^{2} c^{2} + M^{2} c^{4}} \\
& M c^{2} + \Delta E = E + E_{\gamma} = \sqrt{E_{\gamma}^{2} + M^{2} c^{4}} + E_{\gamma} \\
& \Delta E^{2} + 2 M c^{2} \left( \Delta E - E_{\gamma} \right) = 2 \Delta E E_{\gamma} \approx 2 \Delta E^{2} \\
& 2 M c^{2} \left( \Delta E - E_{\gamma} \right) \approx \Delta E^{2} \\
& \frac{\Delta E - E_{\gamma}}{\Delta E} = \frac{\Delta E}{2 M c^{2}}
\end{aligned}
$$

The reaction is expressed as

\[ 
\gamma + \mathrm{A} \rightarrow \mathrm{~A}^{*} 
\]

where \(\mathrm{A}^{*}\) represents the excited state of the particle. For the particle \(A\) to transition to the excited state, the energy in the center of mass system of the incident channel must be equal to the total energy of the excited state. Let \(E_{\gamma}\) and \(p_{\gamma}\) denote the energy and momentum of the \(\gamma\) photon, respectively, where \(E_{\gamma} = p_{\gamma}\). The square of the total energy in the incident channel is:

\[
\begin{gathered}
\left(E_{\gamma} + mc^{2}\right)^{2} - p_{\gamma}^{2}c^{2} = m^{2}c^{4} + 2mc^{2}E_{\gamma} \\
m^{2}c^{4} + 2mc^{2}E_{\gamma} = \left(mc^{2} + \Delta E\right)^{2} = m^{2}c^{4} + \Delta E^{2} + 2mc^{2}\Delta E \\
E_{\gamma} = \Delta E + \frac{\Delta E^{2}}{2mc^{2}}
\end{gathered}
\]

Thus, the energy of the required \(\gamma\) photon is higher than the excitation energy \(\Delta E\) by \(\frac{\Delta E^{2}}{2mc^{2}}\).

The reaction formula is

\[
{ }_{19}^{41} \mathrm{~K}+\mathrm{p} \rightarrow{ }_{20}^{41} \mathrm{Ca}^{*}+\mathrm{n}
\]

The reaction energy is

\[
Q=\left(M(\mathrm{K}) + m_{\mathrm{p}} - M(\mathrm{Ca}^{*}) - m_{\mathrm{n}}\right) c^{2} = \left[M(\mathrm{K}) - M\left(\mathrm{Ca}^{*}\right) - \left(m_{\mathrm{n}} - m_{\mathrm{p}}\right) + m_{\mathrm{e}}\right] c^{2}
\]

The decay formula is

\[
{ }^{41} \mathrm{Ca}^{*} \rightarrow{ }^{41} \mathrm{~K}+\mathrm{e}^{+}+\nu_{\mathrm{e}}
\]

The decay energy is

\[
\begin{gathered}
E_{\mathrm{d}}\left(\beta^{+}\right)=\left[M\left(\mathrm{Ca}^{*}\right)-M(\mathrm{~K})-2 m_{\mathrm{e}}\right] c^{2} \\
M\left(\mathrm{Ca}^{*}\right)-M(\mathrm{~K}) = \left[E_{\mathrm{d}}\left(\beta^{+}\right)+2 m_{\mathrm{e}}\right] c^{2}
\end{gathered}
\]

Substituting into the above equation, we get

\[
\begin{aligned}
Q & =-\left[M(\mathrm{Ca} *)-M(\mathrm{~K})\right] c^{2}-\left(m_{\mathrm{n}}-m_{\mathrm{p}}\right) c^{2}+m_{\mathrm{e}} c^{2} \\
& =-\left[E_{\mathrm{d}}\left(\beta^{+}\right)+2 m_{\mathrm{e}} c^{2}\right]-\left(m_{\mathrm{n}}-m_{\mathrm{p}}\right) c^{2}+m_{\mathrm{e}} c^{2} \\
& =-4.305 \text{ MeV}
\end{aligned}
\]

The threshold energy of the nuclear reaction is

\[
E_{\mathrm{th}}=\frac{A_{\mathrm{A}}+A_{\mathrm{a}}}{A_{\mathrm{A}}}|Q|=4.41 \text{ MeV}
\]

