When $S = \frac{1}{2}$, it is a doublet state, with the component of the total electronic spin angular momentum along the molecular axis being $\Sigma = \frac{1}{2}, -\frac{1}{2}$;  
When $S = \frac{3}{2}$, it is a quartet state, with $\Sigma = \frac{3}{2}, \frac{1}{2}, -\frac{1}{2}, -\frac{3}{2}$.  

The total angular momentum quantum number along the molecular axis is $\Lambda + \Sigma$.  
When $\Lambda=1, \Sigma=\frac{1}{2}, -\frac{1}{2}$, then $\Lambda + \Sigma = \frac{3}{2}, \frac{1/2}$;  
When $\Lambda=1, \Sigma=\frac{3/2}, \frac{1/2}, -\frac{1/2}, -\frac{3/2}$, then $\Lambda + \Sigma = \frac{5/2}, \frac{3/2}, \frac{1/2}, -\frac{1/2}$;  
