The weak interaction reaction rate is given by

$$
\Gamma=2 \pi G_{\mathrm{F}}^{2}|M|^{2} \frac{\mathrm{d} N}{\mathrm{d} E_{0}}
$$

where $\frac{\mathrm{d} N}{\mathrm{d} E_{0}}$ represents the number of final states per unit energy interval, $M$ is the transition matrix element, and $G_{F}$ is the weak interaction coupling constant.  
The two decay modes of the $\pi^{-}$ particle are:

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \pi^{-} \rightarrow \mu^{-}+\bar{\nu}_{\mu} \\
& \pi^{-} \rightarrow \mathrm{e}^{-}+\bar{\nu}_{e}
\end{aligned}
$$

Assuming a four-fermion interaction with a nucleon-antinucleon intermediate state. Considering parity, angular momentum, etc., according to the V-A theory, this coupling is axial vector coupling (A). For A coupling, $M^{2} \approx 1-\beta$, where $\beta$ is the speed of the charged lepton. The phase space factor is

$$
\frac{\mathrm{d} N}{\mathrm{d} E_{0}}=B p^{2} \cdot \frac{\mathrm{d} p}{\mathrm{d} E_{0}}
$$

where $B$ is a constant, and $p$ is the momentum of the charged lepton in the rest frame of the $\pi$ meson. The total energy of the system is

$$
\begin{aligned}
& E_{0}=m_{\pi}=p+\sqrt{p^{2}+m^{2}} \\
& p=\frac{m_{\pi}^{2}-m^{2}}{2 m_{\pi}}
\end{aligned}
$$

Here, $m$ is the rest mass of the lepton, and the neutrino mass is zero. Differentiating the above equation yields

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \mathrm{d} E_{0}=\mathrm{d} p+\frac{p \mathrm{d} p}{\sqrt{p^{2}+m^{2}}}=\frac{E_{0} \mathrm{d} p}{E_{0}-p}=\frac{2 m_{\pi}^{2}}{m_{\pi}^{2}+m^{2}} \mathrm{d} p \\
& \frac{\mathrm{d} p}{\mathrm{d} E_{0}}=\frac{m_{\pi}^{2}+m^{2}}{2 m_{\pi}^{2}} \\
& \beta=\frac{p}{\sqrt{p^{2}+m^{2}}}=\frac{p}{m_{\pi}-p} \\
& 1-\beta=1-\frac{p}{m_{\pi}-p}=\frac{m_{\pi}-2 p}{m_{\pi}-p}=\frac{2 m_{\pi}^{2}-2\left(m_{\pi}^{2}-m^{2}\right)}{2 m_{\pi}^{2}-\left(m_{\pi}^{2}-m^{2}\right)}=\frac{2 m^{2}}{m_{\pi}^{2}+m^{2}}
\end{aligned}
$$

For A coupling, the decay rate $\Gamma$ is

$$
\Gamma \propto(1-\beta) p^{2} \frac{\mathrm{d} p}{\mathrm{d} E_{0}}=\frac{1}{4}\left(\frac{m}{m_{\pi}}\right)^{2}\left(\frac{m_{\pi}^{2}-m^{2}}{m_{\pi}}\right)^{2}
$$

The ratio is

$$
\begin{aligned}
R & =\frac{\Gamma\left(\pi^{-} \rightarrow \mu^{-} \bar{\nu}_{\mu}\right)}{\Gamma\left(\pi^{-} \rightarrow \mathrm{e}^{-} \bar{\nu}_{e}\right)}=\frac{\frac{m_{\mu}^{2}}{4}\left(1-\frac{m_{\mu}^{2}}{m_{\pi}^{2}}\right)^{2}}{\frac{m_{\mathrm{e}}^{2}}{4}\left(1-\frac{m_{\mathrm{e}}^{2}}{m_{\pi}^{2}}\right)^{2}} \\
& =\frac{m_{\mu}^{2}\left(m_{\pi}^{2}-m_{\mu}^{2}\right)^{2}}{m_{\mathrm{e}}^{2}\left(m_{\pi}^{2}-m_{\mathrm{e}}^{2}\right)^{2}}=8.13 \times 10^{3}
\end{aligned}
$$

