Calculate the magnetic moment of the $\mathrm{n}-\mathrm{p}$ system in the pure D state with total angular momentum $J=1$:

$$
\begin{gathered}
\boldsymbol{J} = \boldsymbol{L} + \boldsymbol{S} \\
\boldsymbol{\mu} = \frac{\left(g_{\boldsymbol{L}} \boldsymbol{L} + g_{S} \boldsymbol{S}\right) \cdot \boldsymbol{J}}{J(J+1)} \mu_{\mathrm{N}}
\end{gathered}
$$

Here, $\mu_{\mathrm{N}}$ is the nuclear magneton.\\
We need to determine $g_{\mathrm{L}}$ and $g_{\mathrm{S}}$. First, calculate $g_{S}$, in a similar manner:

$$
\begin{gathered}
\boldsymbol{S} = \boldsymbol{s}_{\mathrm{p}} + \boldsymbol{s}_{\mathrm{n}} \\
\boldsymbol{\mu}_{\mathrm{S}} = \frac{\left(g_{\mathrm{p}} \boldsymbol{s}_{\mathrm{p}} + g_{\mathrm{n}} \boldsymbol{s}_{\mathrm{n}}\right) \cdot \boldsymbol{S}}{S(S+1)} \boldsymbol{S} \mu_{\mathrm{N}} = g_{S} \boldsymbol{S} \mu_{\mathrm{N}}
\end{gathered}
$$

Thus, we find

$$
g_{S} = \frac{g_{\mathrm{p}} \boldsymbol{s}_{\mathrm{p}} \cdot \boldsymbol{S} + g_{\mathrm{n}} \boldsymbol{s}_{\mathrm{n}} \cdot \boldsymbol{S}}{S(S+1)}
$$

Given $s_{\mathrm{n}} = \boldsymbol{S} - \boldsymbol{s}_{\mathrm{p}}$ and $s_{\mathrm{n}}^{2} = \boldsymbol{S}^{2} + \boldsymbol{s}_{\mathrm{p}}^{2} - 2 \boldsymbol{S} \cdot \boldsymbol{s}_{\mathrm{p}}$, we find

$$
\boldsymbol{S} \cdot \boldsymbol{s}_{\mathrm{p}} = \frac{S(S+1) + s_{\mathrm{p}}(s_{\mathrm{p}} + 1) - s_{\mathrm{n}}(s_{\mathrm{n}} + 1)}{2} = 1
$$

Similarly, $\boldsymbol{S} \cdot \mathrm{s}_{\mathrm{n}} = 1$, so we have

$$
g_{S} = \frac{g_{\mathrm{p}} \boldsymbol{s}_{\mathrm{p}} \cdot \boldsymbol{S} + g_{\mathrm{n}} \boldsymbol{s}_{\mathrm{n}} \cdot \boldsymbol{S}}{S(S+1)} = \frac{g_{\mathrm{p}} + g_{\mathrm{n}}}{2}
$$

For $g_{\mathrm{L}}$, since the neutron contributes nothing to the orbital magnetic moment, the proton contributes the entire orbital magnetic moment but only half of the orbital angular momentum, i.e., $g_{\mathrm{L}} = \frac{1}{2}$. Therefore,

$$
\begin{gathered}
\boldsymbol{\mu} = \frac{\left(g_{\boldsymbol{L}} \boldsymbol{L} + \boldsymbol{g}_{\boldsymbol{S}} \boldsymbol{S}\right) \cdot \boldsymbol{J}}{J(J+1)} \mu_{\mathrm{N}} = \frac{1}{2}\left[\frac{\boldsymbol{L} \cdot \boldsymbol{J} + \left(g_{\mathrm{p}} + g_{\mathrm{n}}\right)(\boldsymbol{S} \cdot \boldsymbol{J})}{J(J+1)}\right] \mu_{\mathrm{N}} \\
\boldsymbol{L} \cdot \boldsymbol{J} = \frac{J(J+1) + L(L+1) - S(S+1)}{2} = \frac{1 \times 2 + 2 \times 3 - 1 \times 2}{2} = 3
\end{gathered}
$$

$\boldsymbol{S} \cdot \boldsymbol{J} = \frac{J(J+1) + S(S+1) - L(L+1)}{2} = \frac{1 \times 2 + 1 \times 2 - 2 \times 3}{2} = -1$. Substituting back into the previous equation:

$$
\boldsymbol{\mu} = \frac{1}{2}\left(\frac{3}{2} - \frac{g_{\mathrm{p}} + g_{\mathrm{n}}}{2}\right) \mu_{\mathrm{N}}
$$

From the problem statement:

$$
\begin{gathered}
\mu_{\mathrm{p}} = g_{\mathrm{p}} s_{\mathrm{p}} \mu_{\mathrm{N}} = \frac{1}{2} g_{\mathrm{p}} \mu_{\mathrm{N}} = 2.79 \mu_{\mathrm{N}} \\
\mu_{\mathrm{n}} = g_{\mathrm{n}} s_{\mathrm{n}} \mu_{\mathrm{N}} = \frac{1}{2} g_{\mathrm{n}} \mu_{\mathrm{N}} = -1.91 \mu_{\mathrm{N}}
\end{gathered}
$$

We have $g_{\mathrm{n}} = -3.82$, $g_{\mathrm{p}} = 5.58$. Substituting these into the equation gives:

$$
\mu = \frac{1}{2}\left(\frac{3}{2} - \frac{5.58 - 3.82}{2}\right) \mu_{\mathrm{N}} = 0.31 \mu_{\mathrm{N}}
$$

If we consider protons as an ideal gas, the proton spins can have two orientations, with energies given by:  
When spin is parallel to \(\boldsymbol{B}\), \( E_{\mathrm{p}}=-\mu_{\mathrm{p}} B \)  
When spin is antiparallel to \(\boldsymbol{B}\), \( E_{\mathrm{p}}=+\mu_{\mathrm{p}} B \)  
Where \(\mu_{\mathrm{p}}=\frac{1}{2} g_{\mathrm{p}} \cdot \mu_{\mathrm{N}}=\frac{1}{2} g_{\mathrm{p}} \frac{e \hbar}{2 m_{\mathrm{p}}}\) is the proton magnetic moment. Given that the proton number density \( n \propto \exp \left(\frac{-E_{\mathrm{p}}}{k T}\right) \), we have 

