In the presence of an external magnetic field and the Coulomb field of the nucleus, the Hamiltonian for the electron is  

$$  
H = \frac{(p-e \mathbf{A} / c)^{2}}{2 m} - \frac{e^{2}}{r}  
$$  

Choose the gauge field, $\mathbf{A} = \frac{1}{2} \boldsymbol{B} \times \boldsymbol{r}$, where $\boldsymbol{B}$ is a constant magnetic field. Define $H_{0} = \frac{p^{2}}{2 m} - \frac{e^{2}}{r}$, the Hamiltonian becomes  

$$  
\begin{aligned}  
H &= H_{0} + H_{1}, \quad \boldsymbol{L} = \boldsymbol{r} \times \boldsymbol{p} \\  
H_{1} &= -\frac{e(\boldsymbol{L} \cdot \boldsymbol{B})}{2 m c} + \frac{e^{2}(\boldsymbol{B} \times \boldsymbol{r})^{2}}{8 m c^{2}}  
\end{aligned}  
$$  

Treat $H_{1}$ as a perturbation, the ground state energy shift is  

$$  
\Delta E = \langle 1\mathrm{S}| H_{1}|1\mathrm{S}\rangle = \frac{e^{2}\langle 1\mathrm{S}|(\boldsymbol{B} \times \boldsymbol{r})^{2}|1\mathrm{S}\rangle}{8 m c^{2}}  
$$  

Given $\boldsymbol{L}|1\mathrm{S}\rangle \equiv 0, |1\mathrm{S}\rangle = \left(\pi a^{3}\right)^{-1/2} \mathrm{e}^{-r/a}, a$ is the Bohr radius, the induced magnetic moment caused by $\boldsymbol{B}$ is  

$$  
\begin{gathered}  
\Delta E = \frac{e^{2} B^{2}}{12 \pi m c^{2} a^{3}} \int 4 \pi r^{4} \mathrm{e}^{-2 r / a} \mathrm{d} r = \frac{e^{2} B^{2} a^{2}}{96 m c^{2}} \\  
\mu \equiv -\frac{\partial(\Delta E)}{\partial B} = -\frac{e^{2} a^{2}}{48 m c^{2}} B  
\end{gathered}  
$$

