When striking a stationary target, the invariant mass squared of the system is given by

$$
\begin{aligned}
s & =\left(E_{\mathrm{p}}+m_{\mathrm{p}}\right)^{2}-p_{\mathrm{p}}^{2} \\
& =E_{\mathrm{p}}^{2}-p_{\mathrm{p}}^{2}+2 E_{\mathrm{p}} m_{\mathrm{p}}+m_{\mathrm{p}}^{2} \\
& =2 E_{\mathrm{p}} m_{\mathrm{p}}+2 m_{\mathrm{p}}^{2}
\end{aligned}
$$

Since $s$ is Lorentz invariant, then

$$
2 E_{\mathrm{p}} m_{\mathrm{p}}+2 m_{\mathrm{p}}^{2}=60^{2}
$$

Therefore, the required energy of the incident proton is

$$
E_{\mathrm{p}} = \frac{60^{2} / 2 - m_{\mathrm{p}}^{2}}{m_{\mathrm{p}}} = \frac{1800 - 0.938^{2}}{0.938} = 1918 \mathrm{GeV}
$$

