solution:
For the scattering of protons and neutrons, ignoring their mass difference and considering the non-relativistic case, in the center-of-mass system, both the neutron and the proton have an energy of \( \frac{E_{0}}{4} \), and scattering only changes their angle. Let the scattering angle be \( \theta_{\mathrm{c}} \). In the laboratory system, the velocity and energy of the neutron after the collision are given by

\[
\begin{aligned}
& u^{\prime 2}=\frac{v_{0}^{2}}{2}\left(1+\cos \theta_{\mathrm{c}}\right), \\
& E^{\prime}=\frac{E_{0}}{2}\left(1+\cos \theta_{\mathrm{c}}\right).
\end{aligned}
\]

When \( \theta_{\mathrm{c}} = 0 \), the neutron does not lose energy; when \( \theta_{\mathrm{c}} = \pi \), the neutron loses all its energy. Assuming that the collision is isotropic in the center-of-mass system, the average energy of the neutron after one collision is

\[
\left\langle E_{1}\right\rangle=\frac{E_{0}}{8 \pi} \int_{0}^{\pi} \int_{0}^{2 \pi}(1+\cos \theta) \sin \theta \mathrm{d} \theta \mathrm{~d} \varphi=\frac{E_{0}}{2}
\]

After \( n \) collisions, the average energy of the neutron is

\[
\left\langle E_{n}\right\rangle=\frac{1}{2^{n}} E_{0}
\]

Next, consider the energy distribution function \( \rho(E) \) of the neutron. In the isotropic scattering in the center-of-mass system, the probability of a neutron scattering into \( \mathrm{d} \Omega \) is \( \mathrm{d} \Omega / 4 \pi \), which, in terms of energy distribution, equals \( \frac{\mathrm{d} E_{1}}{E_{0}} \). The probability of the neutron scattering to energies between \( E_{1} \) and \( E_{1}+\mathrm{d} E_{1} \) can be written as \( \rho_{1}(E) \mathrm{d} E_{1} \), where \( \rho_{1}(E) \mathrm{d} E_{1}=\mathrm{d} E_{1} / E_{0} \). Similarly, after the second collision, \( \rho_{2}(E) \mathrm{d} E_{2}=\mathrm{d} E_{2} / E_{1} \). After \( n \) collisions, the energy density function \( \rho_{n}(E) \) is

\[
\rho_{n}(E) \mathrm{d} E=\frac{\mathrm{d} E}{E_{0}} \int \frac{\mathrm{~d} E_{n-1}}{E_{n-1}} \cdots \frac{\mathrm{~d} E_{2}}{E_{2}} \cdot \frac{\mathrm{~d} E_{1}}{E_{1}}
\]

The integration region is \( E_{n} \leqslant E_{n-1} \leqslant \ldots \leqslant E_{1} \leqslant E_{0} \). All integrations are symmetric. The integration results in

\[
\begin{aligned}
\rho_{n}(E)= & \frac{1}{(n-1)!} \int_{E}^{E_{0}} \frac{\mathrm{~d} E_{n-1}}{E_{n-1}} \int_{E}^{E_{0}} \frac{\mathrm{~d} E_{n-2}}{E_{n-2}} \cdots \int_{E}^{E_{0}} \frac{\mathrm{~d} E_{1}}{E_{1}} \\
& =\frac{1}{(n-1)!}\left[\ln \left(\frac{E_{0}}{E}\right)\right]^{n-1}
\end{aligned}
\]

Using subscripts 1 and 2 to denote the incident proton and the stationary proton, the mass of the proton is \(m\). The invariant mass squared of the system is \(\left(\sum E_{i}\right)^{2}-\left(\sum \boldsymbol{p}_{\boldsymbol{i}}\right)^{2}=E^{* 2}\), where \(E^{*}\) is the total energy in the center-of-momentum frame, which is a Lorentz invariant.  

\[
\begin{aligned}
\left(E_{1}+m\right)^{2}-p_{1}^{2}=E^{* 2} \\
E_{1}^{2}+2 m E_{1}+m^{2}-p_{1}^{2}=E^{* 2} \\
E^{* 2}=2 m E_{1}+m^{2}+m^{2}
\end{aligned}
\]

If the final state consists of two remaining protons, the available energy for producing mass is

\[
\begin{aligned}
T & =E^{*}-2 m=\sqrt{2 m E_{1}+2 m^{2}}-2 m \\
& =\sqrt{2 \times 0.938 \times 1000+2 \times 0.938^{2}}-2 \times 0.938 \\
& =41.5 \, \text{GeV}
\end{aligned}
\]

Additionally, when \(E_{1} \gg m\), a rough estimate yields

\[
T=\sqrt{2 m E_{1}}=\sqrt{2000} \approx 45 \, \text{GeV}
\]

