problem:
Between the two particles $\psi(3095)$ and $\psi^{\prime}(3684)$, there exist three $\mathrm{c}\bar{c}$ bound states:

$$
\begin{array}{ll}
\chi_{0}(3410) & J^{\mathrm{PC}}=0^{++} \\
\chi_{1}(3510) & J^{\mathrm{PC}}=1^{++} \\
\chi_{2}(3555) & J^{\mathrm{PC}}=2^{++}
\end{array}
$$

The masses of the particles in parentheses are expressed in MeV.

(2) Assume $\psi^{\prime}$ is produced by $\mathrm{e}^{+} \mathrm{e}^{-}$ collisions. What is the angular distribution of the photon relative to the beam direction in the process $\psi^{\prime} \rightarrow \gamma+\chi_{0}$?

solution:
Using the Breit-Wigner formula

$$
\sigma_{\mathrm{n}} = \pi \lambda^{2} \frac{\Gamma_{\mathrm{n}} \Gamma}{\left(E - E_{0}\right)^{2} + \Gamma^{2} / 4}
$$

where $\lambda$ is the reduced wavelength, $E$ is the total energy of the incident neutron and the $^{3}\mathrm{He}$ system relative to the $^{4}\mathrm{He}$ ground state energy, $E_{0}$ is the resonant energy peak of $^{4}\mathrm{He}$, $\Gamma$ is the total width of the resonance decay, and $\Gamma_{\mathrm{n}}$ is the partial width of the resonance decay into neutrons. Using this equation, the resonance capture cross-section of $^{3}\mathrm{He}$ for thermal neutrons can be calculated. For thermal neutrons in the laboratory, $E_{\mathrm{n}} = 0.025 \, \mathrm{eV}$, giving

$$
\begin{aligned}
\lambda & = \frac{\hbar}{\sqrt{2 \mu E_{\mathrm{n}}}} = \frac{\hbar}{\sqrt{2 \frac{m_{\mathrm{n}} m_{3_{\mathrm{He}}}}{m_{\mathrm{n}} + m_{3_{\mathrm{He}}}} E_{\mathrm{n}}}} = \frac{ch}{\sqrt{\frac{3}{2} E_{\mathrm{n}} m_{\mathrm{n}} c^{2}}} \\
& = \frac{197 \times 10^{-13}}{\sqrt{1.5 \times 940 \times 25 \times 10^{-9}}} = 3.3 \times 10^{-9} \, \text{cm}
\end{aligned}
$$

Since the spin and parity of both the excited and ground states of $^{4}\mathrm{He}$ are $J^{\pi}=0^{+}$, $\Gamma_{\gamma}=0$, the only other decay channel for $^{4}\mathrm{He}$ is decay into a proton, i.e., $\Gamma = \Gamma_{\mathrm{n}} + \Gamma_{\mathrm{p}}$. It is found that $\Gamma_{\mathrm{n}} \approx 150 \mathrm{eV}$, $\Gamma = \Gamma_{\mathrm{n}} + \Gamma_{\mathrm{p}} \approx \Gamma_{\mathrm{p}} = 1.2 \mathrm{MeV}$. From Figure 2.56, we know $E = 20.6 \mathrm{MeV}, E_{0} = 20.1 \mathrm{MeV}$, and finally obtain

$$
\begin{aligned}
\sigma & = \pi \lambda^{2} \frac{\Gamma_{\mathrm{n}} \Gamma}{\left(E - E_{0}\right)^{2} + \Gamma^{2} / 4} \\
& = 3.1416 \times 3.3^{2} \times 10^{-18} \times \frac{150 \times 10^{-6} \times 1.2}{(20.6 - 20.1)^{2} + 1.2^{2} / 4} \\
& \approx 1 \times 10^{-20} \, \text{cm}^{2} = 1 \times 10^{4} \, \text{b}
\end{aligned}
$$

The energy eigenstates of the neutral K mesons are \(|\mathrm{K}_{1}\rangle\) and \(|\mathrm{K}_{2}\rangle\). Any neutral meson can be expressed as a linear combination of \(|\mathrm{K}_{1}\rangle\) and \(|\mathrm{K}_{2}\rangle\), i.e.,

\[
\begin{aligned}
& \Psi(0) = c_{1} |\mathrm{K}_{1}\rangle + c_{2} |\mathrm{K}_{2}\rangle \\
& \Psi(t) = c_{1} |\mathrm{K}_{1}\rangle e^{-\mathrm{i} m_{1} t} e^{-\Gamma_{1} t / 2} + c_{2} |\mathrm{K}_{2}\rangle e^{-\mathrm{i} m_{2} t} e^{-\Gamma_{2} t / 2}
\end{aligned}
\]

where \(m_{1}\) and \(m_{2}\) are the masses of \(\mathrm{K}_{1}\) and \(\mathrm{K}_{2}\), and \(\Gamma_{1}\) and \(\Gamma_{2}\) are their decay widths, with a lifetime \(\tau = \Gamma^{-1}\). According to the problem, at \(t = 0\), a pure \(\mathrm{K}^{0}\) beam exists:

\[
\Psi(0) = |\mathrm{K}^{0}\rangle = \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}(|\mathrm{K}_{1}\rangle + |\mathrm{K}_{2}\rangle)
\]

At time \(t\), the wave function of the beam is given by

\[
\begin{aligned}
\Psi(t) & = \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} |\mathrm{K}_{1}\rangle e^{-\mathrm{i} m_{1} t} e^{-\Gamma_{1} t / 2} + \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} |\mathrm{K}_{2}\rangle e^{-\mathrm{i} m_{2} t} e^{-\Gamma_{2} t / 2} \\
& = \frac{1}{2}(|\mathrm{K}^{0}\rangle + |\overline{\mathrm{K}}^{0}\rangle) e^{-\mathrm{i} m_{1} t} e^{-\Gamma_{1} t / 2} + \frac{1}{2}(|\mathrm{K}^{0}\rangle - |\overline{\mathrm{K}}^{0}\rangle) e^{-\mathrm{i} m_{2} t} e^{-\Gamma_{2} t / 2}
\end{aligned}
\]

Thus, at time \(t\), the ratio of \(|\overline{\mathrm{K}}^{0}\rangle\) to \(|\mathrm{K}^{0}\rangle\) in the neutral K meson beam is

\[
\begin{aligned}
\frac{p(\overline{\mathrm{K}}^{0})}{p(\mathrm{K}^{0})} & = \frac{\left|\langle\Psi(t) \mid \overline{\mathrm{K}}^{0}\rangle\right|^{2}}{\left|\langle\Psi(t) \mid \mathrm{K}^{0}\rangle\right|^{2}} = \frac{\left|e^{-\mathrm{i} m_{1} t - \Gamma_{1} t / 2} - e^{-\mathrm{i} m_{2} t - \Gamma_{2} t / 2}\right|^{2}}{\left|e^{-\mathrm{i} m_{1} t - \Gamma_{1} t / 2} + e^{-\mathrm{i} m_{2} t - \Gamma_{2} t / 2}\right|^{2}} \\
& = \frac{e^{-\Gamma_{1} t} + e^{-\Gamma_{2} t} - 2 e^{-\Gamma t} \cos \Delta m t}{e^{-\Gamma_{1} t} + e^{-\Gamma_{2} t} + 2 e^{-\Gamma t} \cos \Delta m t}
\end{aligned}
\]

where \(\Gamma = \frac{1}{2}(\Gamma_{1} + \Gamma_{2})\) and \(\Delta m = m_{1} - m_{2}\).

(4) The time evolution of the wave function of the neutrino mass eigenstates can be written as

\[
\begin{aligned}
& \left|\nu_{1}(t)\right\rangle=\left|\nu_{1}\right\rangle \mathrm{e}^{-\mathrm{i} E_{1} t} \\
& \left|\nu_{2}(t)\right\rangle=\left|\nu_{2}\right\rangle \mathrm{e}^{-\mathrm{i} E_{2} t}
\end{aligned}
\]

We express the wave functions of type \(a\) and type \(b\) neutrinos in terms of \(\left|\nu_{1}\right\rangle\) and \(\left|\nu_{2}\right\rangle\), as follows:

\[
\begin{aligned}
& \left|\nu_{\mathrm{a}}\right\rangle=\cos \theta\left|\nu_{1}\right\rangle+\sin \theta\left|\nu_{2}\right\rangle \\
& \left|\nu_{\mathrm{b}}\right\rangle=-\sin \theta\left|\nu_{1}\right\rangle+\cos \theta\left|\nu_{2}\right\rangle
\end{aligned}
\]

At time \(t\), the wave functions of type \(a\) and type \(b\) neutrinos are:

\[
\begin{aligned}
& \left|\nu_{\mathrm{a}}(t)\right\rangle=\cos \theta\left|\nu_{1}\right\rangle \mathrm{e}^{-\mathrm{i} E_{1} t}+\sin \theta\left|\nu_{2}\right\rangle \mathrm{e}^{-\mathrm{i} E_{2} t} \\
& \left|\nu_{\mathrm{b}}(t)\right\rangle=-\sin \theta\left|\nu_{1}\right\rangle \mathrm{e}^{-\mathrm{i} E_{1} t}+\cos \theta\left|\nu_{2}\right\rangle \mathrm{e}^{-\mathrm{i} E_{2} t}
\end{aligned}
\]

At time \(t = 0\), a pure beam of type \(a\) neutrinos \(\left|\nu_{\mathrm{a}}\right\rangle\) exists, and at time \(t\), the probabilities of observing type \(a\) and type \(b\) neutrinos are respectively:

\[
\begin{aligned}
p_{\mathrm{a}}(t) & =\left|\left\langle\nu_{\mathrm{a}} \mid \nu_{\mathrm{a}}(t)\right\rangle\right|^{2}=\cos ^{4} \theta+\sin ^{4} \theta+2 \cos ^{2} \theta \sin ^{2} \theta \cos (\Delta E t) \\
& =\left(\cos ^{2} \theta+\sin ^{2} \theta\right)-4 \cos ^{2} \theta \sin ^{2} \theta \sin ^{2}\left(\frac{1}{2} \Delta E t\right) \\
& =1-\left(\sin ^{2} 2 \theta\right) \sin ^{2}\left(\frac{1}{2} \Delta E t\right) \\
p_{\mathrm{b}}(t) & =1-p_{\mathrm{a}}(t)=\sin ^{2} 2 \theta \sin ^{2}\left(\frac{1}{2} \Delta E t\right)
\end{aligned}
\]

where \(\Delta E=E_{1}-E_{2}\). For further analysis, we assume that neutrinos with different mass eigenstates have the same momentum but different energies, and thus different speeds. The coherence length is much greater than the distance to the supernova. By expressing energy as a function of mass, we have:

\[
\begin{aligned}
& E=\sqrt{p^{2}+m^{2}} \approx p+\frac{m^{2}}{2 p} \\
& \Delta E \approx \frac{m_{2}^{2}-m_{1}^{2}}{2 p} \approx \frac{m_{2}^{2}-m_{1}^{2}}{2 \bar{E}_{\nu}}
\end{aligned}
\]

Since the neutrino mass is very small, \(\bar{E}_{\nu}\) is used in place of \(p\) in the equation. Substituting into the probability equations, we obtain:

\[
\begin{gathered}
p_{\mathrm{a}}(t)=1-\sin ^{2} 2 \theta \sin ^{2}\left(\frac{m_{2}^{2}-m_{1}^{2}}{4 \bar{E}_{\nu}} l\right) \\
p_{\mathrm{b}}(t)=\sin ^{2} 2 \theta \sin ^{2}\left(\frac{m_{2}^{2}-m_{1}^{2}}{4 \bar{E}_{\nu}} l\right)
\end{gathered}
\]

where \(l\) is the flight distance. The oscillation length \(l_{0}\) is defined as:

\[
l_{0}=\frac{4 \bar{E}_{\nu}}{m_{2}^{2}-m_{1}^{2}}
\]

Assuming the distance from Earth to the supernova \(D\) is much smaller than the oscillation length \(l_{0}\), and if no significant neutrino oscillation is detected on Earth, the upper limit on the neutrino mass squared difference is:

\[
\begin{gathered}
\frac{m_{2}^{2}-m_{1}^{2}}{4 \bar{E}_{\nu}} l_{0}=\pi \\
\Delta m^{2}=m_{2}^{2}-m_{1}^{2}<\frac{4 \pi \bar{E}_{\nu}}{D}
\end{gathered}
\]

Substituting the specific values, we finally obtain:

\[
\begin{aligned}
\Delta m^{2}<\frac{4 \pi \bar{E}_{\nu}}{D} & =\frac{4 \pi \times 10^{7}}{3 \times 10^{10} \times 3.16 \times 10^{7} \times 1.7 \times 10^{5}} \\
& \approx 0.8 \times 10^{-15}\left(\mathrm{eV}^{2}\right)
\end{aligned}
\]

Utilizing \(\mathrm{cm}^{-1} \approx 2 \times 10^{-11} \mathrm{MeV} = 2 \times 10^{-5} \mathrm{eV}\) in the equation.

In the rest frame of $\eta^{\prime}$, applying conservation laws we derive:

$$
