\boxed{\text{For odd } A \text{ and odd } Z: g_{j} = \begin{cases} 1 - \frac{2.29}{j+1} & j=l-\frac{1}{2} \\ 1 + \frac{2.29}{j} & j=l+\frac{1}{2} \end{cases}, \text{For odd } A \text{ and odd } N: g_{j} = \begin{cases} \frac{1.91}{j+1} & j=l-\frac{1}{2} \\ -\frac{1.91}{j} & j=l+\frac{1}{2} \end{cases}}
\]

problem:
Given the decay of ${}^{17} \mathrm{N}$ to an excited state of ${}^{17} \mathrm{O}^*$, the maximum emitted $\beta$ energy is $3.72 \mathrm{MeV}$. This excited state of ${}^{17} \mathrm{O}^*$ decays by emitting a neutron. Using the following mass difference data and experimental data, calculate the energy level of the emitted neutron.

$$
\begin{gathered}
m\left({}^{17} \mathrm{N}\right)-m\left({}^{17} \mathrm{O}\right)=8.8 \mathrm{MeV} / c^{2} \\
m(\mathrm{n})-m\left({}^{1} \mathrm{H}\right)=0.78 \mathrm{MeV} / c^{2}
\end{gathered}
$$

The energy levels of the excited states of ${}^{16} \mathrm{O}$ are $6.05 \mathrm{MeV}$, $6.13 \mathrm{MeV}$, $6.97 \mathrm{MeV}$, $7.1 \mathrm{MeV}$, and higher levels.

solution:
The energy of the photoelectrons $E_{\mathrm{e}}$ is given by the equation $E_{\mathrm{e}}=E_{\gamma}-W_{\mathrm{i}}$, where $W_{\mathrm{i}}$ is the binding energy of the silver shell. Thus,

$$
\begin{aligned}
E_{\gamma_{2}} & =E_{\mathrm{e}_{1}}+0.025=0.216+0.025=0.241 \, \mathrm{MeV} \\
& =E_{\mathrm{e}_{2}}+0.004=0.237+0.004=0.241 \, \mathrm{MeV}
\end{aligned}
$$

The results obtained from both shell levels are consistent.

The atomic mass difference between ${}^{64} \mathrm{Cu}$ and ${}^{64} \mathrm{Zn}$ is related to the energy of the emitted $\beta^{-}$ particle, $E_{\mathrm{d}}(\beta^{-})$:

$$
\begin{aligned}
E_{\mathrm{d}}(\beta^{-}) & = \Delta M c^{2} = \left[M\left({}^{64} \mathrm{Cu}\right) - M\left({}^{64} \mathrm{Zn}\right)\right] c^{2} \\
& = 573 \mathrm{keV} \\
\Delta M & = M\left({}^{64} \mathrm{Cu}\right) - M\left({}^{64} \mathrm{Zn}\right) = \frac{E_{\mathrm{d}}(\beta^{-})}{c^{2}} = 0.000615 \mathrm{u}
\end{aligned}
$$

problem:
Consider the mixing states of two types of neutrinos, $
u_1$ and $
u_2$, corresponding to the electron and muon Dirac neutrinos, with masses $m_1$ and $m_2$, respectively:
$$
 egin{gathered}

u_{\mathrm{e}}=
u_{1} \cos 	heta+
u_{2} \sin 	heta \

u_{\mu}=-
u_{1} \sin 	heta+
u_{2} \cos 	heta
\end{gathered}
$$
where $	heta$ is called the mixing angle. The mass term of their Hamiltonian is given by
$$
H=m_1  ar{
u}_{1} 
u_{1} + m_2  ar{
u}_{2} 
u_{2}
$$
Express the Hamiltonian matrix elements in the $
u_e$ and $
u_\mu$ representation:
$$
H= ar{
u}_{l} M_{l l^{\prime}} 
u_{l} \quad l, l^{\prime}=e, \mu
$$
to determine the eigenstate masses $m_1$ and $m_2$ and the mixing angle.

solution:
In the representation of $\nu_{\mathrm{e}}$ and $\nu_{\mu}$, the Hamiltonian is:
$$
H=\left(\begin{array}{cc}
M_{\mathrm{ee}} & M_{\mathrm{e} \mu} \\
M_{\mu e} & M_{\mu \mu}
\end{array}\right)
$$
Let $M_{e \mu}=M_{\mu e}$. The eigenvalues of the Hamiltonian can be found from:
$$
\begin{gathered}
\left(\begin{array}{cc}
M_{\mathrm{ee}}-m & M_{\mathrm{e} \mu} \\
M_{\mu e} & M_{\mu \mu}-m
\end{array}\right)=0 \\
m^{2}-\left(M_{\mathrm{ee}}+M_{\mu \mu}\right) m+\left(M_{\mathrm{ee}} M_{\mu \mu}-M_{\mu e}^{2}\right)=0
\end{gathered}
$$

Solving this equation, we obtain:
$$
\begin{aligned}
& m_{1}=\frac{1}{2}\left[\left(M_{\mathrm{ee}}+M_{\mu \mu}\right)-\sqrt{\left(M_{\mathrm{ee}}-M_{\mu \mu}\right)^{2}+4 M_{\mu e}^{2}}\right] \\
& m_{2}=\frac{1}{2}\left[\left(M_{\mathrm{ee}}+M_{\mu \mu}\right)+\sqrt{\left(M_{\mathrm{ee}}-M_{\mu \mu}\right)^{2}+4 M_{\mu e}^{2}}\right]
\end{aligned}
$$

Assuming that in the $\nu_{\mathrm{e}}$ and $\nu_{\mu}$ representation, $\nu_{2}$ is expressed as:
$$
\nu_{2}=\binom{a_{1}}{a_{2}}
$$
we have the equation:
$$
H \nu_{2}=m_{2} \nu_{2}
$$

which implies:
$$
\left(\begin{array}{cc}
M_{\mathrm{ee}} & M_{\mathrm{e} \mu} \\
M_{\mu \mathrm{e}} & M_{\mu \mu}
\end{array}\right)\binom{a_{1}}{a_{2}}=m_{2}\binom{a_{1}}{a_{2}}
$$

With the normalization condition $a_{1}^{2}+a_{2}^{2}=1$, we get:
$$
\begin{aligned}
& a_{1}=\frac{M_{\mu e}}{\sqrt{M_{\mu e}^{2}+\left(m_{2}-M_{\mathrm{ee}}\right)^{2}}} \\
& a_{2}=\frac{m_{2}-M_{\mathrm{ee}}}{\sqrt{M_{\mu e}^{2}+\left(m_{2}-M_{\mathrm{ee}}\right)^{2}}}
\end{aligned}
$$

Using the mixing relations:
$$
\begin{gathered}
\nu_{\mathrm{e}}=\nu_{1} \cos \theta+\nu_{2} \sin \theta \\
\nu_{\mu}=-\nu_{1} \sin \theta+\nu_{2} \cos \theta
\end{gathered}
$$

can be rewritten as:
$$
\begin{aligned}
& \nu_{1}=\nu_{e} \cos \theta-\nu_{\mu} \sin \theta \\
& \nu_{2}=\nu_{e} \sin \theta+\nu_{\mu} \cos \theta
\end{aligned}
$$

Since $\nu_{2}=a_{1} \nu_{\mathrm{e}}+a_{2} \nu_{\mu}$, we find:
$$
\begin{aligned}
\tan \theta=\frac{a_{1}}{a_{2}} & =\frac{M_{\mu e}}{m_{2}-M_{\mathrm{ee}}}=\frac{2 M_{\mu e}}{M_{\mu \mu}-M_{\mathrm{ee}}+\sqrt{\left(M_{\mathrm{ee}}-M_{\mu \mu}\right)^{2}+4 M_{\mu e}^{2}}} \\
\theta & =\arctan \frac{2 M_{\mu e}}{M_{\mu \mu}-M_{\mathrm{ee}}+\sqrt{\left(M_{\mathrm{ee}}-M_{\mu \mu}\right)^{2}+4 M_{\mu e}^{2}}}
\end{aligned}
$$
